"# Chapter 8 — Sound and Music

The last chapter in this book leaves the screen and goes to the speakers. Sound is a first-class citizen in Motoi. Every note is a value; every rhythm is a shape; every song is a Scheme form you can save, share, and edit. The round-trip Alfred keeps naming applies to audio the same way it applies to pixels: what the composer saves is what a text editor sees is what the runtime plays.

Four steps: strike one note, play a chord, compose a rhythm, arrange a whole track. By the end you have written a song in Scheme.

## Why the sound lib exists

Every music tool that ever asked you to `save your project` and stored the answer in a binary blob understood something the compositor didn't: musicians reach for text. A composer scribbling on staff paper is writing symbols in a grammar. A drummer counting `1 e and a 2 e and a` is writing rhythm as text. When your tool respects that, the musician can read their own work.

Motoi's audio verbs take pitches as symbols (`'C4`, `'F#3`), durations as numbers, rhythms as lists. A score is a list of note events. It is Scheme all the way down. You do not have to leave the language to compose music; you compose in the language you already know.

## Problem 1 — Strike a single note

One line. `note/strike` takes a pitch and a duration in milliseconds.

```
(note/strike 'C4 500)
;; => middle C sounds for half a second
```

Pitches are symbols in scientific notation: letter (A through G), optional accidental (`#` or `b`), octave number. `'C4` is middle C. `'A4` is the tuning A above middle C. `'F#3` is F-sharp below middle C.

Duration is milliseconds. 1000 is one second, 500 is half a second, 100 is a short chirp. Try three durations in a row and hear the difference:

```
(note/strike 'C4 100)
(note/strike 'E4 200)
(note/strike 'G4 500)
;; => a short C, a slightly longer E, a lingering G
```

Notice that `note/strike` does not wait for the previous note to finish. If you want the notes to play sequentially, you have to schedule them. That is what problem 3 is about. If you want them to play together, that is a chord — problem 2.

## Problem 2 — Play a chord

`synth/chord` takes a section, a list of pitches, and a duration. All the pitches sound at the same instant.

```
(synth/chord 'strings (list 'C4 'E4 'G4) 1000)
;; => a strings section holding a C-major triad for one second
```

The section decides the timbre. `'strings` is a lush string section. `'woodwinds` is a chamber of flutes and clarinets. `'brass` is punchy horns. Motoi ships several — reach for `'strings` first because it forgives ambiguous chords the best.

Extend the chord to a seventh:

```
(synth/chord 'strings (list 'C4 'E4 'G4 'Bb4) 2000)
;; => a C7 (dominant seventh) held for two seconds
```

Same shape, one extra pitch, one extra beat. You wrote a chord in three parentheses. The lookup table of `pitch symbol -> frequency` is Motoi's; you never touch Hertz.

## Problem 3 — Play a melody, note by note, on a schedule

`at-beat` schedules an action for a specific beat. Combined with `tempo`, you write music in beats rather than in raw milliseconds.

```
(tempo 120)   ;; 120 beats per minute — a walking pace

(at-beat 0 (lambda () (note/strike 'C4 400)))
(at-beat 1 (lambda () (note/strike 'D4 400)))
(at-beat 2 (lambda () (note/strike 'E4 400)))
(at-beat 3 (lambda () (note/strike 'F4 400)))
(at-beat 4 (lambda () (note/strike 'G4 400)))
(at-beat 5 (lambda () (note/strike 'A4 400)))
(at-beat 6 (lambda () (note/strike 'B4 400)))
(at-beat 7 (lambda () (note/strike 'C5 800)))
;; => C major scale, one note per beat
```

That is a scale, spelled out. Now the same scale, built with a loop:

```
(define scale (list 'C4 'D4 'E4 'F4 'G4 'A4 'B4 'C5))

(let loop ((notes scale) (beat 0))
  (if (null? notes)
      'done
      (begin
        (at-beat beat
                 (lambda () (note/strike (car notes) 400)))
        (loop (cdr notes) (+ beat 1)))))
;; => same C major scale, but built from data
```

Now the scale is data. Change the list, change the notes. Reverse the list for a descending scale. Interleave two lists for a two-voice pattern. Every scheduling technique in this chapter reduces music to two ingredients: a list of pitches and a rule for placing them in time.

Motoi's `at-beat` reads the current `tempo` to convert beats into milliseconds. Change `tempo` to `240` and the whole scale plays twice as fast. Change to `60` and it slows to a crawl. Same pitches, different feel.

## Problem 4 (pro) — A song: melody, chords, drums together

A short piece — four measures of a repeating four-chord loop with a melody on top and a drum pattern beneath.

```
(tempo 100)

;; ── chords: I  V  vi  IV  in C major ─────────────────────
(define chord-pattern
  (list
    (list 0  'strings (list 'C3 'E3 'G3))
    (list 4  'strings (list 'G2 'B2 'D3))
    (list 8  'strings (list 'A2 'C3 'E3))
    (list 12 'strings (list 'F2 'A2 'C3))))

(for-each
  (lambda (evt)
    (let ((beat (list-ref evt 0))
          (sect (list-ref evt 1))
          (pit  (list-ref evt 2)))
      (at-beat beat
               (lambda () (synth/chord sect pit 4000)))))
  chord-pattern)

;; ── melody: eighth notes over the changes ────────────────
(define melody
  (list
    ;;   beat  pitch  dur-ms
    (list 0.0  'E4 400)
    (list 0.5  'G4 400)
    (list 1.0  'C5 800)
    (list 2.0  'B4 400)
    (list 2.5  'G4 400)
    (list 3.0  'A4 800)
    (list 4.0  'G4 400)
    (list 4.5  'B4 400)
    (list 5.0  'D5 800)
    (list 6.0  'C5 400)
    (list 6.5  'B4 400)
    (list 7.0  'A4 800)))

(for-each
  (lambda (note)
    (let ((beat (list-ref note 0))
          (pit  (list-ref note 1))
          (dur  (list-ref note 2)))
      (at-beat beat
               (lambda () (note/strike pit dur)))))
  melody)

;; ── drums: kick on 1 and 3, snare on 2 and 4 ─────────────
(define (play-drums-for measures)
  (let loop ((m 0))
    (if (= m measures)
        'done
        (let ((base (* m 4)))
          (at-beat (+ base 0)   (lambda () (synth/808 'kick)))
          (at-beat (+ base 1)   (lambda () (synth/808 'snare)))
          (at-beat (+ base 2)   (lambda () (synth/808 'kick)))
          (at-beat (+ base 3)   (lambda () (synth/808 'snare)))
          (loop (+ m 1))))))

(play-drums-for 4)
```

Read the whole thing. Three layers scheduled independently, one common clock. The chord list places one four-second chord at the start of each measure. The melody list places eighth notes on beats 0, 0.5, 1, and so on — Motoi accepts fractional beats. The drum loop uses `synth/808` — a classic drum machine — to place a kick on odd beats and a snare on even beats for four measures.

Every layer is data. If you want a different chord progression, edit the `chord-pattern` list. If you want the drums to swing, change the beat offsets. If you want a longer song, extend the melody list. Nothing is hidden in a project file; everything is Scheme.

## Capstone — A drum machine driven by keyboard: press `a`/`s`/`d` to layer parts

```
(tempo 120)

(define playing (list))

(define (toggle-part name)
  (if (memv name playing)
      (set! playing (filter (lambda (x) (not (eq? x name))) playing))
      (set! playing (cons name playing))))

(define (schedule-loop bar)
  (let ((base (* bar 4)))
    (when (memv 'kick playing)
      (at-beat (+ base 0) (lambda () (synth/808 'kick)))
      (at-beat (+ base 2) (lambda () (synth/808 'kick))))
    (when (memv 'snare playing)
      (at-beat (+ base 1) (lambda () (synth/808 'snare)))
      (at-beat (+ base 3) (lambda () (synth/808 'snare))))
    (when (memv 'hat playing)
      (at-beat (+ base 0)   (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 0.5) (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 1)   (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 1.5) (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 2)   (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 2.5) (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 3)   (lambda () (synth/808 'hat)))
      (at-beat (+ base 3.5) (lambda () (synth/808 'hat))))))

(big-bang 0                             ;; state is bar number
  (on-tick (lambda (bar)
             (schedule-loop bar)
             (+ bar 1)))
  (on-key  (lambda (bar event)
             (let ((k (list-ref event 1)))
               (cond ((eq? k 'a) (toggle-part 'kick)  bar)
                     ((eq? k 's) (toggle-part 'snare) bar)
                     ((eq? k 'd) (toggle-part 'hat)   bar)
                     (else bar)))))
  (to-draw (lambda (bar)
             (begin-frame 'main)
             (paint-rect (list 0 0) (list 320 240) 'shadow-veil)
             (text/draw \"drum machine\"
                        at: (list 160 40) color: 'petal-pink
                        font: 'big align: 'center)
             (text/draw (string-append \"bar \" (number->string bar))
                        at: (list 160 80) color: 'moss-green
                        font: 'default align: 'center)
             (text/draw (string-append \"parts: \"
                                       (if (null? playing)
                                           \"(silence)\"
                                           (apply string-append
                                                  (map (lambda (p) (string-append (symbol->string p) \" \"))
                                                       playing))))
                        at: (list 160 120) color: 'earth-brown
                        font: 'default align: 'center)
             (text/draw \"[a] kick   [s] snare   [d] hat\"
                        at: (list 160 200) color: 'earth-brown
                        font: 'tiny align: 'center)
             (end-frame 'main))))
```

This is a full instrument. The state is a bar counter. On every tick, `schedule-loop` places the drum hits for the current bar based on which parts are turned on. Keyboard input toggles parts on and off. The HUD displays the current bar and active parts.

Three keys, three drum voices, live composition. You could layer this with the piece from Problem 4 — melody on top, drums driven by hand — and improvise over the progression.

## What's next

This is the last chapter. You have base language, list ops, higher-order functions, recursion, drawing, world-loop, entities, and audio. You can build a game. You can build an instrument. You can build a paint program. You can build a text adventure. Every ingredient in this book composes with every other ingredient — that is Motoi's whole point.

If you want more, `book-of-composition` explores the composer (the round-trip UI kit) in depth, `book-of-motion` walks through animation principles, and `book-of-music` walks through musical form. This book was the on-ramp. Those books are the wide roads.
")
